They frequently assail the Epicurean philosophy, and sometimes attack him by name.⁵ Several oi them, however, were not above imitating his style, and occasionally they made free use of portioris of his work not inconsistent with their creed.⁸

With the complete victory of the Christian doctrine over the Pagan plrilosophies and Gnostic tendencies, Lucretius and his system were lost sight of. But soon after the revival of letters he came into prominence as a popularizerof Epicureanism.
